INstall Prometheus and grafana in k8s cluster


Kubernetes Monitoring Lab: Prometheus + Grafana
Objective: Deploy a production-style monitoring stack in Kubernetes using the
kube-prometheus-stack Helm chart and visualize metrics in Grafana.
Prerequisites
• Working Kubernetes cluster (1 master + 2 workers recommended)

kubectl configured
• Helm installed
• Internet access to pull container images

## Step 1 – Add Helm Repository
helm repo add prometheus-community https://prometheus-community.github.io/helm-charts
helm repo update

## Step 2 – Create Monitoring Namespace
kubectl create namespace monitoring

## Step 3 – Install kube-prometheus-stack
helm install monitoring prometheus-community/kube-prometheus-stack --namespace monitoring

## Step 4 – Verify Monitoring Pods

kubectl get pods -n monitoring
Expected Components
• Prometheus Server
• Grafana
• Alertmanager
• Node Exporter (DaemonSet)
• kube-state-metrics

## Step 5.1 – Access Grafana (clusterip)
kubectl get svc/monitoring-grafana -n monitoring
Open browser: http://monitoring-grafana-clusterip:80
## or ##
## Step 5.2 – Access Grafana (Port Forward)
kubectl port-forward svc/monitoring-grafana 3001:80 -n monitoring
Open browser: http://localhost:3001

## Step 6 – Get Grafana Admin Password
kubectl --namespace monitoring get secrets monitoring-grafana -o jsonpath="{.data.admin-password}" | base64 -d ; echo

## Step 7 – Verify Prometheus Metrics

kubectl port-forward svc/monitoring-kube-prometheus-prometheus 9090:9090 -n monitoring
• Open browser: http://localhost:9090
• Test query: up

## Step 8 – Generate CPU Load (Test Monitoring)

kubectl run cpu-stress --image=polinux/stress --restart=Never -- stress --cpu 2 --timeout 120

## Step 9 – Observe Metrics

kubectl top pod
kubectl top node

• Open Grafana dashboards and observe CPU spike

## Cleanup

kubectl delete pod cpu-stress

helm uninstall monitoring -n monitoring

kubectl delete namespace monitoring

